article.headline: Comets show old poise, rally to victory
article.linkText: Comets rally from 15 down to beat Rockers
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Tina Thompson and the Houston Comets were not
about to panic after falling behind by 15 points.

	   "We came out and decided to be who we are, a good, solid,
championship team,'' Thompson said after scoring 26 points and
sparking the Comets past Cleveland 69-65 in overtime Saturday.

	   Thompson scored four points in overtime to help Houston improve
to 6-0 lifetime at Gund Arena and ruin the revamped Rockers' season
opener.

	   "We wanted to take control, be aggressive,'' Thompson said.
"We were rushing things, a little anxious. We stepped up our
defense and that got our offense going.''

	   A 15-footer by Sheryl Swoopes with 7 seconds left in regulation
gave Houston a 61-59 lead.

	   Penny Taylor, who led Cleveland with a career-high 24 points,
made two free throws with 3.4 seconds left to force overtime.

	   "Yeah, I know, that was great, but we didn't end up winning,''
Taylor said.

	   The Rockers had a chance to force a second overtime, but
Jennifer Rizzotti missed a 10-footer with 3 seconds left.

	   "We knew Houston wasn't going to give up, I mean they did win
four championships,'' said Rizzotti, who finished with 13 points,
five assists and only one turnover.

	   Janeth Arcain hit two free throws with 2 seconds left for
Houston and finished with 17 points.

	   The Comets have won two of their first three games as they seek
to return to league supremacy. Houston won the first four WNBA
titles before losing in the playoffs last year to eventual champion
Los Angeles.

	   "They are a good team, but this was a tough loss for us,''
Rockers coach Dan Hughes said. "We couldn't hold the lead and that
was disappointing. They got to the foul line too many times.''

	   Houston made 18 of 25 free throws compared to 8 of 11 by the
Rockers, who were without four key players from the club that went
22-10 last season and won the Eastern Conference.

	   Center Ann Wauters is still playing in the European
championships, forward Rushia Brown is sidelined with a broken
finger on her right hand and point guard Helen Darling gave birth
to triplets April 13. Forward Eva Nemcova, the Rockers' career
scoring leader, has not signed for her sixth WNBA season.

	   "Still, you could see the growth in our team,'' Hughes said.
"Penny played well and so did Jen. Those are two players that have
never been in those (starting) positions.''

	   A 10-foot jumper by Merlakia Jones gave Cleveland a 46-31 lead
before Thompson took control.

	   The veteran forward hit a turnaround jumper in the lane and
followed with a long 3-pointer to spark Houston on a 13-2 run that
was capped by a 3-pointer by Swoopes that made it 48-44.

	   Swoopes, the 2000 league MVP who missed all of last season with
a knee injury, missed her first six shots before that 3-pointer.

	   "There's no 10-point play in basketball,'' Swoopes said. "We
didn't try and get it all back at once. That was the key.''
